    <div class="body">

      Loved reading this. Brings back a lot of great memories. <br />
<br />
I went to that Fall/Slant 6 show only at the time I had no idea who the Fall were. In fact I remember thinking, &quot;who the hell is this headlining band that's making me pay more than $6 to see Slant 6?&quot; I was so angry I made a point of leaving before the Fall played. Ha! I really wish I stuck around now.<br />
<br />
<br />
Also shortly after the Black Cat opened I remember going to a cafe on U Street called the Zig Zag Cafe. For some reason our waiter mentioned that he heard the Black Cat was having a hard time filling up the place. Twenty years later the Black Cat's still hanging on. Zig Zag Cafe sadly is not.
    </div>

  </div>
      <div class="comment" id="comment-469098">

    <div class="metadata">
      <div class="number"><a href="#comment-469098">5</a></div>
      <div class="author">
        HKRB      </div>
      <div class="date">
        September 12, 2013      </div>

    </div>

    <div class="body">

      Hands down the best venue to play a show in DC. It's even great to play the backstage, which is ideal for smaller/local bands with less of a draw, and you still get treated like royalty with an actual room backstage to hang out in, free beer, half off food, a private bathroom with a shower, gated parking, storage for gear, and no stairs to climb while carrying a 90-lb. bass amp. So many other clubs in DC get this wrong and the Black Cat gets it all right. I love you, Black Cat! Don't eva change!
    </div>

  </div>
