      <div class="comment" id="comment-475380">

    <div class="metadata">
      <div class="number"><a href="#comment-475380">9</a></div>
      <div class="author">
        Mike Fekula      </div>
      <div class="date">
        September 17, 2013      </div>

    </div>

    <div class="body">

         OK, so this was a great article and a trip down memory lane. Too bad that some people cannot speak positively about the Black Cat without trashing other venues. After our beloved DC Punk Demi-God Ian Mackaye, the One who cannot be contradicted, has to &ldquo;inform&rdquo; us about all the supposed limitations of the 930 Club &ndash; all of which never stopped him from playing there &ndash; we then get the remarks from little brother Alec Mackaye, who gratuitously bashes The Bayou: &ldquo;which was a hideous, shithole bar&hellip;&rdquo;  <br />
   Well, I guess it is sacrilege in DC to contradict the Mackaye family but let&rsquo;s just say that some of us have appreciated all of the 930 Club&rsquo;s formatting, with or without the punk demi-gods; and we definitely remember the Bayou differently. I saw my share of punk shows at the Bayou including the Ramones, 999, and Stiff Little Fingers, and completely enjoyed the experience. The Bayou had a fairly diverse format which I assume probably did not include the DC punks so perhaps this is about settling old scores. I guess some of the punks couldn&rsquo;t handle a venue that had the Skip Castro Band with any frequency. In any case, there has always been a number of good clubs in the DC area and as the article pointed out, a lot of them didn&rsquo;t last, but it wasn&rsquo;t for lack of effort. Kudos to Dante Ferrando and the Black Cat for putting the music out there for the people and earning the community support that has allowed them to keep going all these years. 
    </div>

  </div>
      
    
